Key.Original: The AUR 90 is a selective-fire, bullpup rifle with a gas-operated closed bolt originating from Austria, although Australia and Malaysia both produce it under license. It is the primary service rifle of the Australian Defence Force, but is widely exported and can be found in the hands of many nations and non-state actors. The AUR 90 remains chambered in 5.56x45 mm as it was deemed too costly for the platform to undergo a 6.5x39 mm upgrade. Like all modern rifles, it has a modular design that allows it to accommodate a variety of attachments, such as underslung grenade launchers or shotgun modules. There is also a compact model, the AUR 90C, which has a shorter barrel for better handling in cramped conditions, such as crewing a vehicle or engaging in CQB.

Key.Original: The G36K is a polymer, gas-operated rotating bolt, selective-fire carbine originating from Germany. It ultimately lost to the Promet in Livonian service, but remains in use with the German army among other European nations. It was rechambered for 6.5x39 mm caseless and its modular design makes it compatible with a variety of attachments, including underslung grenade launchers or shotgun modules. The G36C is a smaller, compact variant of the standard rifle, equipped with a shorter barrel which is better suited to close-quarters combat, cramped interiors, or special operations.

It was rechambered for 6.5x39 mm caseless and its modular design makes it compatible with a variety of attachments, including underslung grenade launchers or shotgun modules. The G36C is a smaller, compact variant of the standard rifle, equipped with a shorter barrel which is better suited to close-quarters combat, cramped interiors, or special operations.

Key.Original: The NCAR-15 is an unlicensed variant of the Russian AK-15 rifle manufactured in China, primarily for export, since the late 2020’s. It boasts all the improvements of the original rifle over its legendary predecessor, the AK-74, but has been re-chambered in the Chinese 5.8x42 mm cartridge. It can also be fitted with an underslung grenade launcher, and a carbine variant with a shortened barrel exists for usage in tight quarters. Additionally, the RPK-12 has been adapted for the 5.8mm cartridge, and rebranded as the NCAR-15-1. Despite an ongoing legal dispute over the design and production of this rifle, which is prohibited from import into Russia, CSAT has exported the design widely - particularly to junior partners and associate members of the pact, such as Venezuela.

Key.Original: The Fort 650 series of rifles are licensed versions of the Israeli TRG rifles produced by the Chernarusian manufacturer CER Fort, based out of Novigrad, Chernarus. This version of the TRG is chambered in the 6.5x39 mm NATO standard catridge. The Fort-650 series is manufactured in a full length barrel variant, the Fort-652; a shortened barrel variant, the Fort 651; and a variant with an underslung grenade launcher. The Fort-650 series has replaced the AK-74 as the standard issue rifle of the Chernarusian Defense Forces.
